1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:26,190
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambho Dasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambho Dasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambho Dasa

2
00:00:26,660 --> 00:00:32,847
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:32,866 --> 00:00:55,451
So, we've got this Dhammacakkappavattana Sutta, turning of the wheel of the law, and having told us that the way to happiness was not through seeking happiness in sensual pleasures, remember it's not a denial of sensual pleasures, nor is it the pursuit of self-mortification, or worse, punishing the body for it.

4
00:00:56,207 --> 00:01:10,200
And he says he's awakened to the middle way that gives rise to vision, which gives rise to knowledge and leads to peace, to peace, to direct knowledge, to enlightenment, to nibbana.

5
00:01:11,121 --> 00:01:15,805
And then he says, what, monks, is the middle way awakened to by the Tathagata?

6
00:01:16,246 --> 00:01:25,135
So it is this Noble Eightfold Path, right view, right intention or right attitude, right speech, right action, right livelihood,

7
00:01:25,468 --> 00:01:28,832
right effort, right mindfulness, right concentration.

8
00:01:29,813 --> 00:01:32,316
And this is what leads to peace and so on and so forth.

9
00:01:32,637 --> 00:01:36,460
Now he repeats that, so I'll come back to that.

10
00:01:37,242 --> 00:01:40,186
But then he tells us about the noble truths.

11
00:01:40,885 --> 00:01:43,188
Now this monk is the noble truth of suffering.

12
00:01:43,689 --> 00:01:45,290
This is the first noble truth.

13
00:01:45,311 --> 00:01:46,692
There's four of them.

14
00:01:46,712 --> 00:01:52,859
So there's the noble truth of suffering, the cause of suffering, the fact that there is an end to suffering,

15
00:01:53,430 --> 00:02:22,509
and the path leading to that end of suffering so here he's telling us what the noble truth of suffering is the first noble truth birth is suffering aging is suffering illness is suffering death is suffering union with what is displeasing is suffering and separation from what is pleasing

16
00:02:22,979 --> 00:02:23,560
is suffering.

17
00:02:25,241 --> 00:02:29,228
Not to get what one wants is suffering.

18
00:02:29,247 --> 00:02:35,436
In brief, the five aggregates subject to clinging are suffering.

19
00:02:35,455 --> 00:02:42,105
Now books are written on this, but I'll do a little five minute commentary.

20
00:02:42,126 --> 00:02:50,336
So the first four, suffering, birth, aging, illness and death, this of course refers to, goes back to the

21
00:02:50,705 --> 00:03:06,768
mythology around his awakening, where, you know, as a young man in his middle 20s, he comes across, you know, the person who's very sick, a very aged person, and a corpse.

22
00:03:07,508 --> 00:03:08,510
I mean, that's how it's put.

23
00:03:08,550 --> 00:03:17,943
But basically, somewhere in his mid-20s, he woke up to the fact that what was waiting for him was sickness, old age, and death, having been born.

24
00:03:19,122 --> 00:03:22,826
But he puts in here birth, so birth of course is suffering.

25
00:03:23,707 --> 00:03:33,320
I know that maybe with some cesarean sections the baby doesn't suffer that much, but even so there is suffering.

26
00:03:34,102 --> 00:03:38,848
So it's just part of the fabric of life, this suffering.

27
00:03:38,868 --> 00:03:48,200
So here, remember, there's not only just the basic suffering, the dukkha, there's the dukkha dukkhata, which means the suffering of sufferings.

28
00:03:48,737 --> 00:04:17,461
so he's making always a distinction between the facts of life which are the sickness, old age and death which is painful but the suffering is our relationship to it so always remember that it's not as though he's denying that there is pain in life he himself of course never overcame physical pain he died in pain from some sort of gastroenteritis

29
00:04:20,125 --> 00:04:22,427
So that's the main thing.

30
00:04:22,747 --> 00:04:27,254
And these things are really something to contemplate.

31
00:04:28,535 --> 00:04:30,278
It's good to do it once a day.

32
00:04:30,317 --> 00:04:34,262
Just remind ourselves there is sickness, old age and death.

33
00:04:35,964 --> 00:04:38,908
You don't have to get morbid about it.

34
00:04:39,629 --> 00:04:42,031
It's just there is sickness, old age and death.

35
00:04:43,244 --> 00:05:00,211
So every morning after puja, you know, at the end of the puja, before we do the karaniya sutta, the metta sutta, the sutta on loving-kindness, people send me names of people who are either extremely sick or they're dying, you know.

36
00:05:00,232 --> 00:05:06,321
So every morning I read out this list and the list changes and it's just a nice reminder, you know.

37
00:05:09,447 --> 00:05:10,348
A grounding.

38
00:05:13,382 --> 00:05:42,360
then it's more to do with our daily life so there's the union with what is displeasing is suffering in other words being with what you don't like is a pain that's all he's saying it's very simple very straightforward and it's to do again with our attitude to those situations those people those places where we find ourselves where we don't want to be

39
00:05:42,846 --> 00:05:51,439
So remember, it's not the people, it's not the places that are causing the suffering, it's our relationship to them.

40
00:05:51,899 --> 00:05:56,586
And then there's the opposite, separation from what is pleasing.

41
00:05:56,607 --> 00:06:07,182
So not being able to get your coffee when you want it, your tea, not being able to find your friend or somebody you're close to.

42
00:06:07,242 --> 00:06:10,406
So separation from what you love

43
00:06:10,706 --> 00:06:35,718
from what you're attached to is suffering so again it's not the coffee that's causing the suffering or the friend who's not there or the fact that you can't get out to the countryside at this particular time that's not the suffering the suffering is to do with our relationship to it that getting so those two are the opposites

44
00:06:36,086 --> 00:06:41,394
union with what is displeasing and separation from what is pleasing.

45
00:06:42,555 --> 00:06:46,240
And then finally, in a sentence, not to get what you want.

46
00:06:46,759 --> 00:06:52,887
So I'm sure you've come across this phrase to want what you get more than you're always getting what you want.

47
00:06:53,569 --> 00:06:57,153
So wanting what you get moves us towards contentment.

48
00:06:57,353 --> 00:06:58,274
This is the way it is.

49
00:06:58,894 --> 00:07:04,322
And the more we're content with the way things are, the less there is this desire to

50
00:07:04,622 --> 00:07:12,334
to want to seek happiness in the pleasurable things of life, just to be contented.

51
00:07:13,154 --> 00:07:21,766
So the positive side of not to get what one wants is discontent.

52
00:07:23,269 --> 00:07:25,651
The negative side is discontent.

53
00:07:26,312 --> 00:07:31,439
And if we turn that sentence around itself and just begin to appreciate what we have,

54
00:07:31,689 --> 00:07:37,997
to develop a certain gratitude for it, then this contentment rises, this contentment rises.

55
00:07:40,940 --> 00:07:56,999
And my last little e-reminder with the tip of the day, which of course you all read many times, went on about this business of need and of, what was the three words, need, sufficiency.

56
00:07:57,860 --> 00:08:01,444
You come across that now a lot in Buddhist literature, sufficiency,

57
00:08:01,896 --> 00:08:02,877
and greed.

58
00:08:04,180 --> 00:08:05,641
So how do you know what's sufficient?

59
00:08:06,122 --> 00:08:07,944
That leads to contentment.

60
00:08:08,004 --> 00:08:08,846
What is sufficient?

61
00:08:09,827 --> 00:08:13,153
And I suggest in this that don't come back on it from greed.

62
00:08:13,213 --> 00:08:17,718
Don't look at all the things you greed for and then come back to what you think is sufficiency.

63
00:08:18,279 --> 00:08:22,786
Start from the point of view of what you really, really, really need in order to exist.

64
00:08:23,766 --> 00:08:30,216
Considering, for instance, the disasters we've had last year like the flooding in Pakistan and the flooding in Australia.

65
00:08:30,617 --> 00:08:35,082
So what would you grab and take with you which you think you need?

66
00:08:35,903 --> 00:08:38,067
Now that's your basis.

67
00:08:38,586 --> 00:08:42,192
Once that's clear, then you can begin to move up into this area of sufficiency.

68
00:08:42,711 --> 00:08:44,634
So what we need is clothes.

69
00:08:44,653 --> 00:08:48,057
It doesn't matter whether it's rag clothes or just a cloth.

70
00:08:48,077 --> 00:08:56,288
But then, of course, we live in a society and you need certain clothings for certain jobs and relaxation, etc., etc., see?

71
00:08:57,009 --> 00:09:02,774
If you start from that base of what you need, then it's easier to get to a more realistic sufficiency, that's all.

72
00:09:05,217 --> 00:09:11,202
And then finally, this statement, the five aggregates subject to clinging are suffering.

73
00:09:11,222 --> 00:09:13,424
And our books are written on the five aggregates.

74
00:09:14,385 --> 00:09:24,755
The five aggregates is the way the Buddha splits our human experience in the moment, in the moment, for the purpose of showing us where suffering lies.

75
00:09:25,090 --> 00:09:49,528
so obviously there's the body there are feelings both caused by the body and the mind in the body there's perceptions and feeling and perception always rise together then there are these sankāras so these are your conditionings and this is where you'll find will and it's here in the sankāra that there's suffering created or undone

76
00:09:50,115 --> 00:10:19,919
and then there's cognition that which knows so you're aware of what it is you're aware of it's an act of cognition so these five khandhas remember are there with the Buddha the Buddha after enlightenment still had his five khandhas so it's this business of the process of desire the process of attachment to them using them using these five khandhas which is the body and mind

77
00:10:20,474 --> 00:10:45,086
in order to seek some sort of permanent happiness and when we look at what we mean by happiness I think you'll normally come down to a pleasant beautiful state of mind and of course if you associate real happiness with beautiful states of mind then it's a no go is it?

78
00:10:45,126 --> 00:10:46,548
because it keeps changing

79
00:10:47,304 --> 00:10:55,856
And if you could stop the world and say, this is it, I don't want to move on, then you could use the body and mind to reach this wonderful state.

80
00:10:56,597 --> 00:10:57,099
But you can't.

81
00:10:58,200 --> 00:11:05,650
So as soon as you recognize this process of impermanence, then you stop seeking this permanent happiness in the world.

82
00:11:07,113 --> 00:11:11,197
And that's what makes you let go of things easier.

83
00:11:12,100 --> 00:11:14,283
So when you're in a state of happiness, you're happy.

84
00:11:14,822 --> 00:11:15,945
And then after you finish,

85
00:11:16,263 --> 00:11:46,083
you remind yourself that's it it's never going to rise again you're never going to get the same party it just doesn't happen so that's your first noble truth so this is the noble truth of suffering birth is suffering aging is suffering illness is suffering death is suffering

86
00:11:47,582 --> 00:11:51,409
Union or association with what is displeasing is suffering.

87
00:11:52,432 --> 00:11:55,597
Separation from what is pleasing is suffering.

88
00:11:55,618 --> 00:11:58,482
And not to get what one wants is suffering.

89
00:11:58,503 --> 00:12:06,017
In brief, these five aggregates subject to clinging are suffering.

90
00:12:08,841 --> 00:12:11,447
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

91
00:12:12,187 --> 00:12:28,001
may you be fully liberated having perceived most deeply the problem of suffering from all suffering sooner rather than later

